Introduction¶

Wine can be evaluated and characterized by physicochemical properties, which are routinely done by laboratory tests, and also by sensory tests which rely mainly on human experts. Both components are usually part of the wine certification process to ensure quality of the wine market.

As data for both evaluation types is becoming publicly available, it can be used to improve:

  • the wine making process by identifying the most influential factors which contribute to wines being qualified as good
  • target marketing and consumer preference identification and ultimately profitable market selection

Goals¶

The purpose of this study is to test if linear regression can predict wine alcohol level and if logistic regression can predict wine quality based on the remaining independent physicochemical properties in this dataset:

  • is the data suitable
  • are the models statistically sound
  • are the models able to predict outside the training dataset

Important findings from the info summary:

  • Features are on different scales chlorides and total sulfur dioxide providing the extremes.
  • Features are not normally distributed.
  • Free sulfur dioxide and total sulfur dioxide have large std indicating dispersed data and/or extreme outliers.
  • Density values are in a very narrow range of ~0.99 to ~ 1.00.
  • Quality does not cover all the values in range 0-10, only 3-8.
  • All the variables are right skewed, except for density. Residual sugar and chlorides appear to be extremely right skewed.
  • Citric acid stands out for possibly very flat peak/fat tails.
  • Residual sugar, chlorides stand out for possibly very steep peak.

Checking variable correlations. * next to the value indicates significance based on p-value (P<0.005) - this is intentionally 10 times smaller than the usual 0.05 cut-off point, because larger sample sizes generally lead to smaller p-values (statistical tests were originally designed for samples in tens and hundreds, not thousands).

In [11]:
eda.make_corr_matrix()
eda.draw_correlation()

There is a number of concerning high correlations between independent variables which is not good for a regression model:

  • pH with fixed acidity, citric acidity and density
  • density with fixed acidity, pH, and alcohol (the alcohol correlation is not a concern when alcohol is the dependent variable but is a concern when quality is the dependent variable)
  • fixed acidity, volatile acidity and citric acid all have medium to strong positive or negative correlations

Since there are multiple correlations between independent variables, which is a risk for multicollinearity, I am also checking variance inflation factor (VIF) for the original data as well as data with different rescaling approaches.

This data transformation would be the most suitable for the purpose of the statistical model transparency and interpretability of the coefficients. However it does not mean that the predicting power of this model would be the best.

Linear Regression (Alcohol)¶

For linear regression I am choosing to try the data without transformations and standardized data for comparison.

I am excluding quality feature from this linear regression, because it would introduce data leakage: quality is estimated by human experts during tasting taking into consideration all the physicochemical properties including alcohol, so in a way quality has already been exposed to the 'alcohol information'.

The following models are using statsmodels OLS function.

Running base case linear regression with all the variables and no transformations.

Model interpretation:

  • The R2 value of 0.68 suggests that approximately 68% of the total variability in the dependent variable (alcohol) can be explained by the independent variables included in the model.
  • Significant F-statistic p-value also indicates that the model overall has predictory power.
  • Significant Omnibus p-value indicates that the model residuals are not normally distributed. Jarque-Bera significant p-value also indicates non-normal residual distribution based on skewness and kurtosis measures.
  • Durbin-Watsone evaluates residual autocorrelation, where the result around 2 suggest no autocorrelation.
  • Possible multicollinearity issue indicated by high Condition number.

Coefficients in the linear regression represent the estimated effect or impact of the independent variables on the alcohol dependent variable. These coefficients indicate the change in the mean value of alcohol associated with a one-unit change in the corresponding independent variable, while holding other variables constant. Based on the p-values all the independent variable coefficients area significantly different from 0, except for the free sulfur dioxide, the confidence interval for which extends over the 0 mark [-0.006, 0.004]. For the positive coefficients (fixed acidity, volatile acidity, citric acid, residual sugar, pH, sulphates) there is a positive association between the independent variable and the dependent variable. An increase in the independent variable is associated with an increase in the dependent variable. For the negative coefficients (chlorides, free sulfur dioxide, total sulfur dioxide), an increase in the independent variable is associated with a decrease in the dependent variable.

The magnitude of the coefficient represents the size of the effect. Larger coefficients indicate a stronger impact of the independent variable on the dependent variable. Density variable deserves special attention in this model because of the coefficient size, being -626. The reasons for the extreme coefficient size are several:

  • the density feature has a very narrow range of values ~0.99 to ~ 1.00 the difference between observations being often just about 0.001 or less. while alcohol values range between 8-15
  • however, density feature also has the strongest correlation with alcohol
  • combining these two effects without rescaling the data results in the extreme coefficient size.

The density coefficient also has impact on the intercept value being extreme in the opposite direction (615). The intercept represents the estimated mean value of alcohol when all independent variables are zero (as a baseline or starting point for the dependent variable), but since the density coefficient 'subtracts' 626 from the baseline, this explains the size of the intercept.

Drawing predicted value versus residual plot and residual histogram to check residual normality and homoscedasticity (constant variance across the range of predicted values). Drawing the same plot for train data and test data.

In [18]:
reg1.draw_train_residuals()
reg1.predict_linear()
reg1.draw_test_residuals()

Visually both train and tests data residuals appear normally distributed.

However in both cases visual inspection does not confirm that the variance of the residuals is constant (homoscedastic). It appears that variance of the residuals is smaller for low values of dependent variable.

Checking the normal distribution for residuals with a Shapiro-Wilk test for train and test sets. H0: residuals are from a normal distribution.

In [19]:
reg1.check_train_residual_normality()

0.0
In [20]:
reg1.check_test_residual_normality()

0.8774

For the test set we cannot reject the H0 that residuals are from a normal distribution. However for the train set we have to reject the H0, which I would think is possibly at least partially is because the large size of the data set (with large datasets p values automatically become smaller) and partially because of the lack of symmetry and extra kurtosis.

In terms of the coefficient interpretation this model differs from the base case with untransformed data.

When the variables are standardized, their means are centered at 0 and their standard deviations are scaled to 1. In this scenario, the interpretation of the coefficients changes as they represent the change in the dependent variable in terms of standard deviations, rather than the original units of measurement. The coefficients for the standardized independent variables represent the change in the alcohol variable in terms of standard deviations associated with a one-standard-deviation increase in the corresponding independent variable, while holding other variables constant.

This model has the same explanatory power in terms of R2 as the one with data without transformation.

This model fixed the issues related to:

  • multicollinearity as the Condition number is down to 5.5.
  • extreme coefficient value for density and the intercept (as the data is rescaled to similar scales).

However this model did not fix the issues with residual normality and heteroscedasticity. Significant Omnibus p-value indicates that the model residuals are not normally distributed. Jarque-Bera significant p-value also indicates non-normal residual distribution based on skewness and kurtosis measures.

Logistic regression (Quality)¶

Logistic regression is more suitable to the quality variable, because it is categorical. I am choosing to run a simplified version of the logistic regression where I am trying to predict only two classes - poor quality and good quality. For that purpose the quality column is recoded into 0 for poor quality which I define as quality score <=5 and 1 for good quality which I define as quality score >5. The threshold is chosen this way to create balanced categories for 0 and 1 based on the original quality data distribution (see EDA).

I also make a second data set with log transformation to be used as an alternative in the following logistic regression models for comparison.

data["quality"] = np.where(data["quality"] > 5, 1, 0)

Model interpretation:

  • The pseudo R-squared value of 0.2577 indicates the model explains around 26% of the variability in the dependent variable, which is quite low.
  • The log-likelihood for this model is -557.90. Comparing this to the null model log-likelihood (-751.62), the model is a statistically significant improvement based on the likelihood ratio test p-value of almost zero.
  • In summary, even though the model is explaining only about a quarter of the variability observed in quality. The extremely low p-value confirms the model as a whole is statistically significant in predicting the dependent variable compared to random chance.

The coefficient interpretation differs from the linear regression - these coefficients are log(odds) coefficients. To the the actual odds coefficients I will be taking exponents in the next section. At 95% confidence level, the significant coefficients are only:

  • volatile acidity(negative relationship),
  • chlorides(negative),
  • total sulfur dioxide(negative),
  • sulphates(positive),
  • alcohol(positive).

The intercept coefficient is not significant.

Although there was variability of the ods factors among models, they all show very similar metrics:

  • All the logistic model alternatives were only able to explain about a quarter of the variability observed in quality based on pseudo R2.
  • But in all cases the extremely low p-value of log likelihood confirms the model as a whole is statistically significant in predicting the dependent variable compared to random chance.
  • The predicting metrics is indicating that the models are well balanced (similar accuracy, precision, recall all above 0.7) and performing relatively well, although could be greater.

Log transformation of the data did not contribute significantly to the improvement of the model.

Conclusions¶

Data suitability:

  • The data provides a large dataset for the regression models even after removing duplicates.
  • Several independent variables have strong correlations with the dependent variables indicating that the model would have at least some explanatory power.
  • The quality variable classes are unbalanced with very few very low and very high values, thus making multinomial logistic regression difficult.
  • There are strong enough correlations between several independent variables to raise concerns about multicollinearity in modeling.
  • Different variables are on very different scales, to the extent that is impacts VIF and contributes to multicollinearity. Standard scaler is the only data scaling that fixes all the large VIF values.

Model statistical soundness:

  • The linear models with untransformed data suffer from multicollinearity, which is fixed by the standard rescaling.
  • All the linear models violate the assumptions of normal residual distribution and homoscedasticity. Data transformations did not solve this.
  • The linear models have similarly high explanatory power based on R2 with or without the transformation.
  • Multicollinearity present in the linear model with data transformation makes it difficult to interpret the coefficient effects independently from one another.
  • All the logistic models have quite low explanatory power based on pseudo R2 value. Log data transformation does not solve that problem.

Model ability to predict:

  • All the linear models perform very similarly in terms of the test MSE and test R2. Standardization of data only very marginally improves the performance.
  • All the logistic models perform very similarly based on the accuracy, precision, recall, F1 measures. Log transformation does not add value in terms of predictions.
  • All the logistic model performance is well balanced in terms of accuracy, precision, recall values being very similar.

Overall it is interesting to conclude that the violation of statistical assumptions in a model does not mean that the predicting ability is necessarily compromised. Statistical soundness of the model appear to be a separate concern from the performance optimization in a model. The goal of the model should be set clearly at the beginning of a modeling exercise to guide the work in a most productive manner.

Practical business application:

  • For alcohol quantity in wine the strongest impact is from density variable (with a negative relationship). Then the next by the coefficient size are pH(positive), sulphates(positive), chlorides(negative).
  • For wine quality the strongest predictors are:
    • sulphates with the factor 15.9 indicating very strong positive effect on odds
    • alcohol the factor 2.5 indicating strong positive effect
    • total sulfur dioxide the factor 0.98 indicating a negative effect
    • volatile acidity the factor 0.07 indicating a negative effect
    • chlorides the factor 0.01 indicating a negative effect

Next steps and improvements¶

  • Look into more detailed charts for understanding the regression models e.g. added variable plot (for nonlinearity in the relationship between one variable and the outcome), component plus residual plot (analyze one variable with others fixed).
  • Explore the influential values' impact on the model.
  • Try other approaches for model building/variable selection like stepwise.
  • Try ridge, lasso, robust regression approaches for possible model improvements.
  • Try multinomial logistic regression to predict multiple categories.
